0107a9b0-70c9-4276-975d-fb7a76d0ff25.0fa6e37f-486b-4aef-a7cf-ed092b2e07cd.description=
Retrieves row indexes if the row satisfies the specified condition in an Excel document. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\: 
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet.
Default value\: Sheet1
    hasHeader - If Yes, then the first row of the document is expected to be the header row.
Valid values\: yes, no
Default value\: yes
    firstRowIndex - The index of the first row in the Excel worksheet, including the header row.
Default value\: 0
    columnIndextoQuery - The column index to search in.
    operator - The math operators. 
Valid values\: \=\=, \!\= for string comparison; \=\=, \!\=, <,<\=,>,>\= for numeric comparison.
Default vaue\: \=\=
    value - The value to search in the specified column. If left blank, it means an empty value.

Results\: 
    returnResult - This is the primary result. Return a list of row indexes that satisfied the specified condition.
    rowsCount - The number of the row indexes returned.

Responses\: 
    success - The row indexes were retrieved successfully. 
    failure - Failed to retrieve the row indexes.

Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. Observed that in some Excel worksheet, the first couple of rows are used for title. So added firstRowIndex input.
3. Value in date type has to be in the format of "YYYY/MM/DD", "YYYY/DD/MM HH\:MM\:SS" or "YYYY/MM/DD HH\:MM".
4. Value in time type has to be in the format of "HH\:MM\:SS" or "HH\:MM".
5. If there's any merged region existed in the worksheet, the cells in the merged region are not considered except the top left cell.

0107a9b0-70c9-4276-975d-fb7a76d0ff25.2005b0b8-fc3a-4ce4-b231-c4e9dd19f9c2.description=Modifies the specified cell with new value in an Excel document. XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. Inputs\: excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document. Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet. Default value\: Sheet1 rowIndex - A list of row indexes. Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25 Default value\: from the index of the first row to the index of the last row of the Excel worksheet. columnIndex - A list of column indexes. Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25 Default value\: from 0 to the index of the last column in the Excel worksheet. newValue\: A comma delimited list of data to write to the specified cell. The size of the newValue list should be the same as the size of columnIndex input. columnDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the columns of the returnResult. Default value\: , (comma) isText\: If set to true it will store newValue as text in excel. Default value\: false Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the number of rows that were affected. Responses\: success - The cell data was modified successfully. failure - Failed to modify the cell data. incomplete - Not all the cells specified were modified. Notes\: 1. All the index inputs are 0 based. 2. For the indexes in rowIndex input that is less than the first data row index or greater than the last row index in the worksheet, the operation trims those row indexes. 3. For the indexes in columnIndex input that is less than 0 or greater than the last column index in a row, the operation trims those column indexes. 4. If columnIndex input is empty, the size of the newValue list should be the same as column count in the worksheet. 5. If the newValue is a numeric value, the cell modified is set to numeric type. 6. The operation will attempt to convert a given date or time value to a date or time value in excel, if it fails to do so, it will insert the input directly. 7. If there's any change in the worksheet, all values of formula type cells are updated. 8. If there's any merged region existed in the worksheet, only the top left cell can be modified. 0107a9b0-70c9-4276-975d-fb7a76d0ff25.23d223f5-5a6d-4b7b-bf1b-c441a5dc67b0.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.
0107a9b0-70c9-4276-975d-fb7a76d0ff25.3826f579-927b-4740-b4f7-1a234e4ceeca.description=

Displays a message to the user.

Inputs\:
  message - The message text to display
  title - The title on the message window. Defaults to "Status message".

Responses\:
  Always returns success.

Examples\:
  In order to display the message "Finished" to the user, go to the 
  detail screen for the input named "message" and change the Otherwise option
  from Prompt User to Use Constant.  Then enter the text "Finished" into the
  Constant Value field.

  References to flow variables in the Contant Value field are expanded so that
  the text may be dynamic.  Flow variable references are of the form
  ${variable}.  For example, the text\:
     ${count} systems were modified 
  could be used to display a message about the number of systems that were
  repaired, whose value is in the flow variable "count".

  When the message is displayed, it will properly render any embedded html
  tags, which permits creating messages with more advanced formatting.  For 
  example to display a message in italics you could use\:
    This is important
  or to display a message in red\:
    This is really  important

  You can create messages that contain multiple lines by entering a multiple
  line message in the Constant Value field, or by using HTML 
 tags for line
  breaks.  Note that \n characters are displayed literally and are not used for
  creating multiple lines.

0107a9b0-70c9-4276-975d-fb7a76d0ff25.dd1bcd18-9788-4e82-bf0d-954c34881c71.description=
Retrieves the cell data with specified row index and column index in an Excel document. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\:
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet. 
Default value\: Sheet1
    hasHeader - If Yes, then the first row of the document is expected to be the header row. 
Valid values\: yes, no
Default value\: Yes
    firstRowIndex - The index of the first row in the Excel worksheet, including the header row.
Default value\: 0
    rowIndex - A list of row indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default Value\: from the index of the first row  to the index of the last row in the Excel worksheet.
    columnIndex - A list of column indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default value\: from 0 to the index of the last column in the Excel worksheet.
    rowDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the rows of the returnResult.
Default value\: | (pipe)
    columnDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the columns of the returnResult.
Default value\: , (comma)
    enablingRoundingFunction - If the value is set to true, then the selected cells containing decimal numbers will be rounded to 2 decimals digits.
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the cell data retrieved from Excel document.
    header - A delimited list of column names of data being returned if hasHeader is set to Yes. 
    rowsCount - The number of the rows returned.
    columnsCount - The number of the columns returned.

Responses\:
    success - The cell data was retrieved successfully.
    failure - Failed to retrieve the cell data.

Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. Observed that in some Excel worksheet, the first couple of rows are used for title. So added firstRowIndex input.
3. For the indexes in rowIndex input that is less than the first data row index or greater than the last row index in the worksheet, the operation trims those row indexes.
4. For the indexes in columnIndex input that is less than 0 or greater than the last column index in a row, the operation trims those column indexes.
5. The cell data with fraction format shows as double value in returnResult.
